    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-12-06T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-12-06T12:00:00-05:00" n="332"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d332">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MDH1">D. H. Miller</persName> to
                            <persName corresp="#p_HCEM1">Colonel E. M. House</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-06T17:00:00+00:00">6
                            December, 1918—evening</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Following for you from <persName corresp="#p_WSW1">Wiseman</persName> (<hi
                        rend="smallcaps">Starts</hi>) I understand <persName corresp="#p_BAJ1"
                        >Balfour</persName> has telegraphed you suggesting that it would help him if
                    you would intimate that the President would be glad for <persName
                        corresp="#p_RERDI1">Reading</persName> to be in Paris during peace
                    discussions. Owing to political difficulties I do not think <persName
                        corresp="#p_RERDI1">Reading</persName> can be a delegate, but believe he
                    will accept the position of High Commissioner on Anglo-American affairs, but
                        <persName corresp="#p_BAJ1">Balfour</persName> thinks there will be
                    opposition even to that appointment.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
